      "text": "Based on the analysis of the available data:\n\n1.  **Molecular Formula & MW**: The sample has the formula **C9H9N** and a molecular weight of approximately **131.07 Da**. The degree of unsaturation (DBE) is 6.\n2.  **13C NMR**: The spectrum displays 9 carbon signals. The peak at **33.16 ppm** is characteristic of an **N-methyl** group (N-CH3). The aromatic/alkenic region contains 8 carbons, with specific shifts at **103.27 ppm** and **109.79 ppm** that are highly diagnostic for the **C3** and **C7** positions of an **indole** nucleus. The quaternary carbon at **139.96 ppm** (C7a) and CH at **128.23 ppm** (C2) also align perfectly with literature values for the indole skeleton.\n3.  **1H NMR**: The singlet at **3.88 ppm (3H)** confirms the presence of an **N-methyl** group (consistent with N-methylindole). The doublets at **7.18 ppm** and **6.68 ppm** with **J ~ 3.0 Hz** correspond to the **H2** and **H3** protons of the pyrrole ring, showing the typical coupling constant for 1-substituted indoles. The peaks at **7.84 ppm (d)** and **7.44 ppm (d)** correspond to the protons on the benzene ring (likely H4 and H7). The singlet at **10.06 ppm** is anomalous for pure 1-methylindole in standard CDCl3 (where no proton typically exceeds 8 ppm), but given the perfect match of the 13C fingerprint and the N-Me signal, this may represent a specific experimental condition (e.g., salt formation, solvent effect) or an artifact in the dataset. No other C9H9N isomer (such as C-methylindoles or quinoline derivatives) accounts for the high-field N-Me signal and the specific indole 13C pattern simultaneously.\n\nTherefore, the structure is identified as **1-Methylindole**.\n\nFINAL_RESULT:\n  UUID: 22abbcad-8512-4d6c-b69d-500915e3cafc\n  PREDICTED_SMILES: Cn1ccc2ccccc21\n  CONFIDENCE: 0.85\n  REASON_BRIEF: The 13C NMR spectrum perfectly matches the fingerprint of 1-methylindole (particularly the shielded C3 at 103 ppm and N-Me at 33 ppm). The 1H NMR confirms an N-Me group (3.88 ppm) and pyrrole ring protons (J=3.0 Hz), supporting this assignment despite the anomalous chemical shift of one aromatic proton.",
